Module kivakit.kernel
Package com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.language.values.count

Class Count

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.kivakit.kernel.language.values.count.Count
All Implemented Interfaces:
Countable, DoubleQuantizable, Maximizable<Count>, Minimizable<Count>, Quantizable, AsString, Serializable, Comparable<Count>
Direct Known Subclasses:
BitCount, Bytes, Estimate, Maximum, Minimum
public class Count extends Object implements Countable, Comparable<Count>, Quantizable, Maximizable<Count>, Minimizable<Count>, AsString, Serializable
Represents a count of something. Counts have useful properties that primitive values like long and int do not have. Count objects are guaranteed to be positive values, so it is not possible to have a Count of -1. Counts also have a variety of useful methods for comparison, conversion, mathematical operations and other conveniences. By implementing the Quantizable interface, they inherit operations and are interoperable with all other objects that consume Quantizables.

Count objects are cheaper than they might seem for two reasons:

  • (1) low count constants and powers of two can be accessed as constant objects (like _1024 or _15) and values up to 65,536 are cached so that no new object is created if you call count(long)
  • (2) allocation of count objects higher than 65,536 are cheap in Java due to the design of generational garbage collectors. This said, there will be occasions where Count objects are not desirable (for example, inside a doubly nested loop) and sometimes they may improve a public API method or constructor, while the internal representation is a primitive value for efficiency. As always, the best approach is to use objects until a problem shows up in a profiler like YourKit.
